Summary: Exoplanet searches have typically focused on main sequence stars. Direct imaging has probed young planets, but what about the other extreme: planets around highly evolved stars? Only one planet has been found transiting a white dwarf. Searches have avoided binary stars due to fear of a diluted signal. However, secular interactions with a binary companion may be the only way of obtaining a short period planet around a white dwarf. We have carefully constructed a sample of white dwarfs in binaries, for which we have a planet-finding sensitivity on either the white dwarf or its main sequence companion. We predict roughly 5 discoveries in 3500 binaries. Any individual discovery with bear significance, and we will interpret our results in the context of planetary dynamics and stellar evolution.
